revision.text:
==English==
[[File:Yggdrasil.jpg|thumb|An illustration depicting Yggdrasil, by Oluf Olufsen Bagge, for 1847, ''Northern Antiquities'', an English translation of the Prose Edda]]
===Alternative forms===
* {{alter|en|Yggdrasill}}
===Etymology===
Borrowed from {{bor|en|non|Yggdrasill}}; commonly accepted as being composed {{m|non|yggr||terrible}} + {{m|non|drasill||steed}}, where “steed” refers to a hanging tree or possibly from {{m|ine-pro|*dʰer-||to hold, support}}.
===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/ˈɪɡdɹəsɪl/}}
** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-Yggdrasil.wav|Audio (Berkshire, UK)}}
===Proper noun===
{{en-proper noun}}
# {{lb|en|Norse mythology}} An immense [[ash]] [[tree]] that is central in [[Norse]] [[cosmology]], believed to connect the nine worlds.
#* '''1863''', ''The London Quarterly Review'', Volumes 113-114, [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=IuwRAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA1-PA117&dq=%22yggdrasil%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=kAYmVd2XGYPo8gX_uYCwCQ&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=%22yggdrasil%22&f=false page 117],
#*: Yet it is not easy to pluck out the heart of its mystery; and the descriptions of certain ancient representatives of '''Yggdrasil''' do not lessen the difficulty.
#* '''1963''', [[w:Spike Milligan|Spike Milligan]], ''[[w:Puckoon|Puckoon]]'', chapter 1, page 1,
#*: With nostrils and legs akimbo, she towered over him like some human '''Yggdrasill''', blotting out the sun.
#* '''1996''', Carolyne Larrington (editor and translator), ''The Seeress's Prophecy'', ''[[w:Poetic Edda|The Poetic Edda]]'', [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=nBzuQZ4MCPIC&pg=PA6&dq=%22I+know+that+an+ash-tree+stands+called+Yggdrasill,%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=0wMmVd_wIMLg8AW8n4CYCA&ved=0CDYQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=%22I%20know%20that%20an%20ash-tree%20stands%20called%20Yggdrasill%2C%22&f=false page 6],
#*: I know that an ash-tree stands called '''Yggdrasill''',
#*: a high tree, soaked with shining loam;
#*: from there come the dews which fall in the valley,
#*: ever green, it stands over the well of fate.
#* '''2007''', Bob Curran, Ian Daniels, ''Walking with the Green Man: Father of the Forest, Spirit of Nature'', [https://web.archive.org/web/20160311040930/https://books.google.com.au/books?id=mRAYt2Q6CcIC&pg=PA66&dq=%22yggdrasil%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=kAYmVd2XGYPo8gX_uYCwCQ&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=%22yggdrasil%22&f=false page 66],
#*: In Norse mythology, for example, the World Tree, or '''Yggdrasil''', connected the nine existences that straddled the worlds of gods and men with its mighty roots. '''Yggdrasil''' was reputedly a gigantic ash tree (and was the central feature of Norse cosmology), around the base of which the serpent Níôhöggr had twisted its body.
#* '''2007''', J. A. Hunsinger, ''The Settlers: An Axe of Iron Novel'', [https://web.archive.org/web/20160310090550/https://books.google.com.au/books?id=p-u4Kq4Md3wC&pg=PA333&dq=%22yggdrasil%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=kAYmVd2XGYPo8gX_uYCwCQ&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=%22yggdrasil%22&f=false page 333],
#*: “'''Yggdrasil'''!” Gudbjartur's voice was filled with awe. “It is '''Yggdrasil''', the world-tree!” He looked at Halfdan, his eyes wide. “The Sacred Grove is here in this land!”
